Paleomagnetic Field Tests for 'Possible Eoarchean records of the geomagnetic field preserved in the Isua Supracrustal Belt, southern west Greenland'¶

This notebook outlines the analyses used for the pseudo-baked contact tests, fold test and reversal tests outlined in our paper. All of our data were analysed using PMagPy, and details of each approach can be found in the PMagPy cookbook

To start with, make sure you have everything imported to run PMagPy:

In [1]:
import pmagpy.pmag as pmag
import pmagpy.pmagplotlib as pmagplotlib
import pmagpy.ipmag as ipmag
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt # our plotting buddy
from pmagpy import convert_2_magic as convert
import numpy as np # the fabulous NumPy package
import pandas as pd # and of course Pandas
has_basemap, Basemap = pmag.import_basemap()
has_cartopy, Cartopy = pmag.import_cartopy()
from IPython.display import Image
%matplotlib inline

Passed Pseudo-Baked Contact Tests¶

In this section, we will look at the data for our 'pseudo' baked contact tests. We sampled banded iron formation (BIF) intruded by Ameralik dykes that were emplaced 3.26-3.5 Ga.
However, the dykes were metamorphosed at 2.85 Ga, overprinting their magnetization so we do not use them in our analysis. Therefore we compare 'baked BIF' (close to the intrusion) with 'unbaked BIF' (far from the intrusion) to determine whether the paleomagnetic directions are sufficiently different to verify that the unbaked BIF still retains its 3.69 Ga remanence prior to dyke emplacement.

For each test, there are two .txt files named 'sitename_unbaked.txt' and 'sitename_baked.txt' that contain the declinations and inclinations from each site.

Site 6A¶

Firstly, the unbaked and baked data are loaded and named 'directions_A' and 'directions_B' respectively. We then calculate the fisher mean and alpha95 value (shown by the stars and large circles, respectively) and plot these along with the directional data for each specimen in red for baked directions and blue for unbaked directions.

In [2]:
directions_A=np.loadtxt('6A_unbaked.txt', delimiter = ',').transpose()
directions_B=np.loadtxt('6A_baked.txt', delimiter = ',').transpose()
decA=directions_A[0]
incA=directions_A[1]
decB=directions_B[0]
incB=directions_B[1]
#calculate Fisher mean and alpha 95
fisherA=ipmag.fisher_mean(dec=decA,inc=incA)
fisherB=ipmag.fisher_mean(dec=decB,inc=incB)
# plots stereonet of data
ipmag.plot_net(1)
directions_A=np.loadtxt('6A_unbaked.txt', delimiter = ',')
directions_B=np.loadtxt('6A_baked.txt', delimiter = ',')
ipmag.plot_di(di_block=directions_A,color='blue',edge='black')
ipmag.plot_di(di_block=directions_B,color='red',edge='black')
ipmag.plot_di_mean(dec=fisherA['dec'],inc=fisherA['inc'],a95=fisherA['alpha95'],\
                  marker='*',color='blue',markersize=50)
ipmag.plot_di_mean(dec=fisherB['dec'],inc=fisherB['inc'],a95=fisherB['alpha95'],\
                  marker='*',color='red',markersize=50)

Next, we check to see if the unbaked and baked directions are statistically similar using Watson's V test. For our pseudo-baked contact test to pass, the critical value of V (blude dashed line) must be less than Watson's V value for our data (green line). This means that the unbaked and baked directions are distinct to 95% confidence. So at site 6A, our pseudo-baked contact test passes.

In [3]:
directions_A=np.loadtxt('6A_unbaked.txt', delimiter = ',')
directions_B=np.loadtxt('6A_baked.txt', delimiter = ',')
# Watson V test
plt.figure(1,(5,5))
ipmag.common_mean_watson(directions_A,directions_B,plot='yes')

Fold Test¶

In this section we run a fold test on our passed pseudo baked contact tests from sites 8A/A, 6A and C. We take the basal bedding measurement from each site (note that this needs to be inputted into PMagPy as a dip and a dip direction, rather than a strike and dip) and use this to untilt our unbaked BIF directions to paleohorizontal.

Unbaked Directions from 6A, 8A/A and C¶

The following commands take the unbaked BIF directions from sites 6A, 8A/A and C, and their basal bedding measurements and then gradually untilt them from -10 to 110% untilting.

The geographic stereonet shows the directions prior to tilt correction, and the tilt corrected stereonet shows the directions after 100% tilt correction.

$\tau_1$ is then calculated, which is a measure of how clustered the directions are regardless of their polarity. The green curve shows that clustering shows a strong increase between 80-110% untilting, indicating a positive fold test (i.e., the unbaked directions were acquired prior to the folding event).

In [13]:
fold_unbaked=np.loadtxt('Fold_test_unbaked.txt', delimiter = ',')
ipmag.bootstrap_fold_test(fold_unbaked,num_sims=1000, min_untilt=-11, max_untilt=111)

doing  1000  iterations...please be patient.....

tightest grouping of vectors obtained at (95% confidence bounds):
79 - 110 percent unfolding
range of all bootstrap samples: 
31  -  110 percent unfolding

Baked Directions from 6A, 8A/A and C¶

In this section we run a fold test on our passed pseudo baked contact tests from sites 8A/A, 6A and C. We take the basal bedding measurement from each site (note that this needs to be inputted into PMagPy as a dip and a dip direction, rather than a strike and dip) and use this to untilt our baked BIF directions to paleohorizontal.

The following commands take the baked BIF directions from sites 6A, 8A/A and C, and their basal bedding measurements and then gradually untilt them from -10 to 110% untilting.

The geographic stereonet shows the directions prior to tilt correction, and the tilt corrected stereonet shows the directions after 100% tilt correction.

$\tau_1$ is then calculated, which is a measure of how clustered the directions are regardless of their polarity. The green curve shows that clustering shows a strong increase between -5-45% untilting, indicating a negative fold test (i.e., the baked directions were acquired after the folding event, most likely during the emplacement of the Ameralik dykes).

Reversal Test¶

In this section we run two types of reversal test to verify whether the tilt-corrected, unbaked BIF directions recovered from 8A/A and C are truly antipodal to 6A, indicating a reversing field.

Tilt-corrected, unbaked directions from Sites 6A, 8A/A and C¶

First, we load in the two sets of antipodal directions as 'directions_A' and 'directionsB' and calculate the fisher mean and $\alpha{95}$ of each distribution. The data for sites 8A/A and C are plotted in blue, and the data for site 6A is plotted in red on the stereonet below. The fisher statistics for each set of directions are also printed above the stereonet.

In [15]:
directions_A=np.loadtxt('6A_tilt_corrected_directions.txt', delimiter = ',').transpose()
directions_B=np.loadtxt('8A_A_and_C_tilt_corrected_directions.txt', delimiter = ',').transpose()
decA=directions_A[0]
incA=directions_A[1]
decB=directions_B[0]
incB=directions_B[1]
#calculate Fisher mean and alpha 95
fisherA=ipmag.fisher_mean(dec=decA,inc=incA)
print('6A fisher statistics:', 'mean dec =', round(fisherA['dec']), 'mean inc =', round(fisherA['inc']),
      'n = ', fisherA['n'], 'k =', round(fisherA['k']))
print('8A/A and C fisher statistics:', 'mean dec =', round(fisherB['dec']), 'mean inc =', round(fisherB['inc']),
      'n = ', fisherB['n'], 'k =', round(fisherB['k']))
fisherB=ipmag.fisher_mean(dec=decB,inc=incB)
# plots stereonet of data
ipmag.plot_net(1)
directions_A=np.loadtxt('6A_tilt_corrected_directions.txt', delimiter = ',')
directions_B=np.loadtxt('8A_A_and_C_tilt_corrected_directions.txt', delimiter = ',')
ipmag.plot_di(di_block=directions_A,color='red',edge='black')
ipmag.plot_di(di_block=directions_B,color='blue',edge='black')
ipmag.plot_di_mean(dec=fisherA['dec'],inc=fisherA['inc'],a95=fisherA['alpha95'],\
                  marker='*',color='red',markersize=50)
ipmag.plot_di_mean(dec=fisherB['dec'],inc=fisherB['inc'],a95=fisherB['alpha95'],\
                  marker='*',color='blue',markersize=50)

6A fisher statistics: mean dec = 53 mean inc = -31 n =  4 k = 15
8A/A and C fisher statistics: mean dec = 135 mean inc = 28 n =  13 k = 1

We then randomly sample the fisher distributions represented by the red and blue datasets 4 and 14 times to reflect the number of data points from our three sites and call these 'normal_directions' (to represent data from sites 8A/A and C) and 'reversed_directions' (to represent data from site 6A). We then combine these directions as 'combined_directions' and run a reversal test to determine whether, if the reversed directions were flipped 180 degrees, we can consider the two sets of directions to be the same. Since the three directional components, x,y and z overlap (as shown by the cumulative distributions) we can consider the reversal test to have passed with 95% confidence.

In [16]:
normal_directions = ipmag.fishrot(k=15, n=4, dec=53, inc=-31)
reversed_directions = ipmag.fishrot(k=5, n=14, dec=263, inc=29)

combined_directions = np.concatenate((normal_directions, reversed_directions))

ipmag.reversal_test_bootstrap(di_block=combined_directions, 
                              plot_stereo=True)

Pass
Out[16]:
1

We also carried out a second reversal test using Watson's V test. Again, the two sets of antipodal directions are named 'directions_A' (for data from site 6A) and 'directions_B' (for data from sites 8A/A and C). These directions are then combined in 'combined_directions' and the reversal test is carried out to see if the two directions can be distinguished if they are rotated to the same polarity. Since the critical value of V (blue dashed line) is greater than the value of V calculated from the directional data, we cannot distinguish the two directions with 95% confidence, again indicating a passed reversal test.

In [17]:
directions_A=np.loadtxt('6A_tilt_corrected_directions.txt', delimiter = ',')
directions_B=np.loadtxt('8A_A_and_C_tilt_corrected_directions.txt', delimiter = ',')
combined_directions = np.concatenate((directions_A, directions_B))
ipmag.reversal_test_MM1990(di_block=combined_directions, plot_CDF=True, plot_stereo=True)
